            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340515-20-person278">
                  CHARLES 
                  SCOTCHMER
               <interp inst="t18340515-20-person278" type="surname" value="SCOTCHMER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340515-20-person278" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340515-20-person278" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (police-sergeant G 125). On the<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183405150018"></xptr>19th of April, about eleven o'clock in the forenoon, I was on duty in White-cross-street - I saw the prisoner at the corner, talking to a young man - the prisoner had these books under his arm - he looked towards me, and walked into Beech-street - I followed, and asked where he got the books - he said in Chick-lane, where he bought them - I said I did not believe him, and took him to the station - in going along, I again asked him where he bought them - he said, in Petticoat-lane - I asked if he could show me the person - he said no; but it was a young man, about eighteen years of age - on the 22d of April, when we were at Worship-street, there was something mentioned about a flannel jacket, and the prisoner said he never wore one; but on the Tuesday and Wednesday before I had seen him with one on.</p>
               <p>JOHN CHIDLEY. I am a <rs id="t18340515-20-viclabel102" type="occupation">bookseller</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340515-20-victim277 t18340515-20-viclabel102"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18340515-20-crimeloc103">Goswell-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18340515-20-crimeloc103" type="placeName" value="Goswell-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18340515-20-crimeloc103" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340515-20-off100 t18340515-20-crimeloc103"></join>. These books are mine - I had seen them a day or two before - I missed them along with some others - I am quite positive they are mine - they were a distance inside the shop quite sufficient to protect them, unless some person had reached a great way in - they are a translation of Klopstock's Messiah.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340515-20-person279">
                  ALFRED 
                  WALKER
               <interp inst="t18340515-20-person279" type="surname" value="WALKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340515-20-person279" type="given" value="ALFRED"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340515-20-person279" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am twelve years old - I know the nature of an oath - I am errand-boy to the prosecutor - on that Friday evening I saw a boy come in and take this bundle of books from the little counter - I never saw him before - I think he was taller than the prisoner, and dressed in a flannel jacket; but I could not well see how tall he was, as he was kneeling down - this was on the Friday night, and on Saturday morning the prisoner was taken.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was going down Petticoat-lane to make an exchange for my coat; I saw these books selling by a boy about eighteen years of age; he was showing them to a parcel of Jews. I asked what he wanted for them: he said a shilling. I said I would give him ten-pence for them, and I bought them. The next morning I was going along with them, and was stopped. I had borrowed the flannel jacket to wear for a day or two, while I had this coat repaired under the arm.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18340515-20-verdict104" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340515-20-verdict104" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
